        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(browser): read Chrome version from PE metadata on Windows",
        "body": "## Description\n\nFixes #87312\n\n`openclaw doctor` reports \"Could not determine the installed Chrome version\" even when Chrome is installed at the expected path with correct version metadata (Chrome 148.x in this case).\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe `readBrowserVersion` function on Windows runs `chrome.exe --version` to determine the installed version. Launching Chrome this way can fail on Windows because:\n- Chrome may attempt to show a GUI or conflict with an already-running instance\n- The process startup can be slow and hit the timeout\n- Chrome's Windows process model differs from macOS/Linux where `--version` returns immediately\n\n## Fix\n\nAdded a Windows-specific code path that reads file version metadata directly from the PE executable using PowerShell (Get-Item).VersionInfo.ProductVersion, which:\n- Is instant (no process launch)\n- Works correctly with all Chrome versions including 148+\n- Falls back to `wmic` if PowerShell is unavailable\n\nThe `chrome.exe --version` fallback remains as a last resort.\n\n## Testing\n\n- Windows 11 with Chrome 148.0.7778.179 at default install path\n- `openclaw doctor` now correctly detects \"Detected Chrome 148.0.7778.179\"\n- No change to macOS or Linux behavior\n",
        "branch": "fix/chrome-version-detection-windows",
        "head_sha": "22baa8413e99a14a33475838e69111502b44521b",
